<P>They now walked on; and, when they entered the
lane, they had the plea&s;ure to ob&s;erve they were not
pur&s;ued. She then &s;aid to Camilla, &startq;You mu&s;t be &s;ur|pri&s;ed
to &s;ee any one out, and unprotected, at this late
hour; but I had employed my&s;elf, unthinkingly, in
reading &s;ome letters from a dear and ab&s;ent friend, and
forgot the quick pa&s;&s;age of time.&endq;</P>
<P>A man in a livery now appearing at &s;ome di&s;tance,
&s;he ha&s;tily &s;ummoned him, and demanded where was
the carriage?</P>
<P>In the $oad, he an&s;wered, where &s;he had left it, at
the end of the la$e.</P>
<P>She then took the hand of Camilla, and with a &s;mile
of the utmo&s;t &s;oftne&s;s &s;aid, &startq;When the &s;hock I have
&s;uffered is a little over, I mu&s;t &s;urely cea&s;e to lament I
have &s;u&s;tained it, &s;ince it has brought to me &s;uch &s;weet
&s;uccour. Where may I find you to-morrow, to repeat
my thanks?</P>
<P>Camilla an&s;wered, &startq;&s;he was going to Tunbridge im|mediately,
but knew not yet where &s;he &s;hould lodge.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Tunbridge!&endq; &s;he repeated; I am there my&s;elf; I
&s;hall ea&s;ily find you out to-morrow morning, for I &s;hall
know no re&s;t till I have &s;een you again.&endq;</P>
<P>She then a&s;ked her name, and, with the mo&s;t touch|ing
