<P>&startq;What I don't under&s;tand in the matter is, that
there reading of letters by the light of the moon;&endq; &s;aid
Mr. Dennel. &startq;Where's the nece&s;&s;ity of doing that,
for a per&s;on that can afford to keep her own coach and
&s;ervants?</P>
<P>Mr. Dennel was a man as unfavoured by nature as he
was uncultivated by art. He had been accepted as a
hu&s;band by the &s;i&s;ter of Mr. Arlbery, merely on ac|count
of a large fortune, which he had acquired in bu|&s;ine&s;s.
The marriage, like mo&s;t others made upon &s;uch
terms, was as little happy in its progre&s;&s;ion as honour|able
in its commencement; and Mi&s;s Dennel, born and
educated amid&s;t dome&s;tic di&s;&s;ention, which robbed her
