<P>&startq;A&s;k Mr. Dennel,&endq; an&s;wered &s;he negligently;
&startq;he's the only pay-ma&s;ter ju&s;t now.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="121" REF="122">
Mr. Dennel turned round, and was going to walk
away; but Mrs. Arlbery, taking him by the arm,
&s;aid, &startq;my good friend, how many tickets &s;hall Sir
Sedley give you?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Me! none at all.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O &s;ie! every body goes to the ma&s;ter of the cere|monies'
ball. Come, you &s;hall have &s;ix. You can't
po&s;&s;ibly take le&s;s.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Six! What &s;hould I do with them?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Why you and your daughter will u&s;e two, and four
you mu&s;t give away.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;What for?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Was ever &s;uch a que&s;tion? To do what's proper
and right, and hand&s;ome and gallant.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O, as to all that, it's what I don't under&s;tand.
It's out of my way.&endq;</P>
<P>He would then have made off; but Mrs. Arlbery,
piqued to &s;ucceed, held him fa&s;t, and &s;aid: &startq;Come,
if you'll be good, I'll be good too, and you &s;hall have
a plain joint of meat at the bottom of the table every
