go, or choo&s;e to go, or approve of going, I cannot,
in &s;ober earne&s;tne&s;s, &s;ee you compelled. Nothing is &s;o
dete&s;table as forcing people to be amu&s;ed. Come, now
for Knowle.&endq;</P>
<P>Sir Sedley was then putting up his tickets; but the
Major, taking one of them out of his hand, pre&s;ented
it to Camilla, &s;aying: &startq;Let the ladies take their tick|ets,
now, and &s;ettle with us afterwards.&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla felt extremely provoked, yet not knowing
how to re&s;i&s;t, took the ticket; but, turning pointedly
from the Major to Sir Sedley, &s;aid: &startq;I am your debt|or,
then, &s;ir, a guinea&mdash;the &s;malle&s;t part, indeed, of
what I owe you, though all I can pay!&endq; And &s;he
then re&s;olved to borrow that &s;um immediately of Mrs.
Arlbery.</P>
<P>Sir Sedley began to think &s;he grew hand&s;omer every
moment: and, contrary to his e&s;tabli&s;hed and &s;y&s;tematic
inattention, upon hearing the &s;ound of the carriages,
